      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1065">
               <p>Hopper, a native of <placeName>County Durham</placeName>, was converted under
                  Methodist preaching in <date when="1743">1743</date>. That same year
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> made him a
                  class-leader and he began to preach locally. For this, as well as for teaching
                  school without a licence, he was summoned before the ecclesiastical court in
                     <placeName>Durham</placeName>. He continued either to preach or conduct a
                  class-meeting every evening after school, and began to make preaching visits for
                  twenty or thirty miles around. About <date when="1750">1750</date> he become a
                  full-time <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerant</seg>, even though married, and emerged
                  as one of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s
                  longest serving and most trusted lay preachers. See <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>,
                  571–72; <hi rend="italic">EMP</hi>, 1:179–239; <hi rend="italic">Minutes</hi>
                  (post-Wesley, <date when="1802">1802</date>), 2:122–23; and Vickers, <hi
                     rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 164.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
